Spectral Partitioning of Bipartite Graphs

Typical example of bipartite graph is a graph obtained from a collection of documents presented as a term × document matrix.

Prerequisites

The reader should be familiar with k-means algorithm and spectral graph partitioning theory and algorithms.

Competences

The reader should be able to apply spectral partitioning of bipartite graphs to data clustering problems.

Credits. The notebook was initially derived from M.Sc. Thesis of Ivančica Mirošević.

16.5 μs

Definitions

Undirected bipartite graph G is a triplet G=(T,D,E), where T={t1,⋯,tm} and D={d1,...,dn} are two sets of vertices and E={(ti,dj):ti∈R,dj∈D}, is a set of edges.

G

is weighted if there is weight ω(e) associated with each edge e∈E.

For example, D is a set of documents, T is a set of terms (words) and edge e=(ti,dj) exists if document dj contains term ti. Weight ω(e) can be number of appearances of the term ti in the document dj.

A term-by-document-matrix is a matrix A∈Rm×n with Aij=ω((ti,dj)).

13.9 μs

Facts

  1. The weight matrix of G is

W=[0AAT0]

.

  1. The Laplacian matrix of G is

L=[Δ1−A−ATΔ2],

where Δ1 and Δ2 are diagonal matrices with elements

Δ1,ii=∑j=1nAij,i=1,…,m,

Δ2,jj=∑i=1mAij,j=1,…,n.

  1. The normalized Laplacian matrix of G is

Ln=[I−Δ1−12AΔ2−12−Δ2−12ATΔ1−12I]≡[I−An−AnTI].

29.0 μs

  1. Let λ be an eigenvalue of Ln with an eigenvector w=[uv], where u∈Rm v∈Rn.

Then Lnw=λw implies Anv=(1−λ)u and AnTu=(1−λ)v. Vice versa, if (u,σ,v) is a singular triplet of An, then 1−σ is an eigenvalue of Ln with (non-unit) eigenvector w=[uv].

  1. The second largest singular value of An corresponds to the second smallest eigenvalue of Ln, and computing the former is numerically more stable.

18.4 μs

Bipartitioning algorithm

  1. For given A compute An.

  2. Compute singular vectors of An, u[2] and v[2], which correspond to the second largest singular value, σ2(An).

  3. Assign the partitions T={T1,T2} and D={D1,D2} according to the signs of u[2] and v[2]. The pair (T,D) is now partitioned as {(T1,D1),(T2,D2)}.

28.9 μs

Recursive bipartitioning algorithm

  1. Compute the bipartition π={(T1,D1),(T2,D2)} of (T,D). Set the counter c=2.

  2. While c<k repeat

    • compute bipartitions of each of the subpartitions of (T,D),

    • among all (c+1)-subpartitions, choose the one with the smallest pcut(πc+1) or ncut(πc+1), respectively.

    • Set c=c+1

  3. Stop

16.1 μs

Multipartitioning algorithm

  1. For given A compute An.

  2. Compute k left and right singular vectors, u[1],…,u[k] and v[1],…,v[k], which correspond to k largest singular values σ1≥⋯≥σk of An.

  3. Partition the rows of matrices Δ1−12[u[1]…u[k]] and Δ2−12[v[1]…v[k]] with the k-means algorithm.
